Hughes continued to produce a high volume of work across multiple genres until his death on May 22, 1967. As the first Black American to earn a living solely by writing, his legacy includes more than 60 books, social commentary and pioneering work that has inspired generations. /end

Hughesâ€™ political associations led him to be targeted during the Cold War. In 1953, he testified before Senator Joseph McCarthyâ€™s Subcommittee and distanced himself from overt radicalism. Nevertheless, he remained a mentor to younger civil rights activists and writers such as Alice Walker. /8

During the 1930s, Hughes was an advocate for the Scottsboro Boys, nine Black youths falsely accused of rape. From 1942 to 1962, he wrote a weekly column for the Chicago Defender featuring an Everyman character named Jesse B. Semple. He used humor to critique segregation and economic injustice. /7

Unlike many contemporaries, Hughes wrote for and about the Black working class, capturing the â€œlow-down folksâ€ with dignity. In his 1926 essay, â€œThe Negro Artist and the Racial Mountain,â€ he declared that Black artists should express their â€œindividual dark-skinned selves without fear or shame.â€ /6

Shortly after graduating from high school in 1920, and while still a teenager, Hughes wrote one of his most famous poems, â€œThe Negro Speaks of Rivers.â€ Published in 1921 in the NAACPâ€™s magazine The Crisis, it garnered him national acclaim before he had even published his first book. /5

During high school, Hughes wrote his first piece of jazz poetry, â€œWhen Sue Wears Red.â€ This early work began to showcase the jazz-like rhythms and improvisation that would later make him famous. He used syncopated rhythms and musical structures to reflect the African American cultural experience. /4

Hughes began experimenting with writing while attending grammar school in Lincoln, Ill., where he was elected class poet. He had never in fact written a poem, but this title sparked his interest in experimenting with poetry. As a teen, he also began writing his first short stories and plays. /3

Langston Hughesâ€™ mother left him in the care of his maternal grandmother in Lawrence, Kan., while she traveled to find employment. His grandmother instilled in him a sense of pride and a duty to help other African Americans. His childhood was lonely, and he found solace in reading. /2

The group gained national attention in 1965 during clashes with the Klan in Bogalusa. The local Klan was powerful, and the Deacons were there to defend civil rights activists who were being attacked and harassed. They also provided security for the 1966 March Against Fear in Mississippi. /5

The Deacons for Defense and Justice established a strong, armed presence, successfully neutralizing Klan activity in some areas. They fostered a sense of dignity and self-determination and inspired other Black Power groups, though they conflicted with mainstream nonviolent strategies. /4

The groupâ€™s mission was to counter Klan tactics and protect activists and Black families facing threats, operating where local law enforcement wouldnâ€™t or couldnâ€™t help. The Deacons for Defense and Justice was founded in 1964 in Jonesboro, La. The first affiliated chapter was formed in Bogalusa, La., on Feb. 21, 1965 â€” the day after Malcolm Xâ€™s assassination.
